https://github.com/libgdx/libgdx/commit/da8fb9e108abdf593f02258f0b3f52093124c937 seems to break the normal lifecycle handling of the Timer.
If you add a trivial Task to an application (I tested using lwjgl)

```
Timer.schedule(new Task() {
@Override
public void run() {
Gdx.app.error("bug", "task::run");
}
}, 1, 1);
```

then cause the application to pause() by clicking on another window, then resume the app by clicking on the app window, you will see that the task is no longer running. Removing checkStatics() makes the Timer behave correctly again.

In GWT if you destroy a body with joints before destroying the joints, the joints will not properly destroy, causing a runtime error.

This problem doesn't appear to occur in Desktop.

According to iforce2d.net, when a body is destroyed, its joints should be cleaned up automatically:
http://www.iforce2d.net/b2dtut/joints-overview  See "Cleaning up"

The runtime error happens in the debug renderer.

```
GwtApplication: exception: (TypeError)
 stack: TypeError: Cannot read property 'body_0' of null
     at $getTransform
     at $drawJoint
     at $renderBodies
```

Example code:

```
package com.mygdx.game;

import com.badlogic.gdx.ApplicationAdapter;
import com.badlogic.gdx.Gdx;
import com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.GL20;
import com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.OrthographicCamera;
import com.badlogic.gdx.math.Matrix4;
import com.badlogic.gdx.math.Vector2;
import com.badlogic.gdx.physics.box2d.*;
import com.badlogic.gdx.physics.box2d.joints.WeldJointDef;

public class MyGdxGame extends ApplicationAdapter {



    private World world;
    private Box2DDebugRenderer debugRenderer;
    private OrthographicCamera cam;
    private final Matrix4 projection = new Matrix4();

    private Body bodyA;
    private float time = 0.0f;
    private boolean destroyed;

    @Override
    public void create () {
        cam = new OrthographicCamera(Gdx.graphics.getWidth(), Gdx.graphics.getHeight());
        world = new World(Vector2.Zero, true);
        debugRenderer = new Box2DDebugRenderer();

        createDude();
    }

    private void createDude() {
        CircleShape shape = new CircleShape();
        shape.setRadius(1.0f);

        FixtureDef fixture = new FixtureDef();
        fixture.shape = shape;
        fixture.density = 1.0f;

        BodyDef bodyDef = new BodyDef();
        bodyDef.allowSleep = true;
        bodyDef.type = BodyDef.BodyType.DynamicBody;

        bodyA = world.createBody(bodyDef);
        bodyA.createFixture(fixture);

        Body bodyB = world.createBody(bodyDef);
        bodyB.createFixture(fixture);

        WeldJointDef jointDef = new WeldJointDef();
        jointDef.bodyA = bodyA;
        jointDef.bodyB = bodyB;
        jointDef.localAnchorB.set(-3, 0);

        world.createJoint(jointDef);
    }

    @Override
    public void render () {
        Gdx.gl.glClearColor(0, 0, 0, 1);
        Gdx.gl.glClear(GL20.GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT);

        world.step(Gdx.graphics.getDeltaTime(), 1, 1);
        projection.set(cam.combined);
        projection.scl(30f);
        debugRenderer.render(world, projection);

        if (!destroyed) {
            time += Gdx.graphics.getDeltaTime();
            if (time > 3.0f) {
                Gdx.app.log("MyGdxGame", "Destroying bodyA");
                // Will cause html version to crash.
                // Does not cause Desktop to crash.
                world.destroyBody(bodyA);
                destroyed = true;
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Using latest libGDX nightlies on Desktop I am experiencing a strange issue. It seems to me this could be a bug in libGDX. But I am not 100% sure, so I would like to hear your opinion.

So in my game I am rendering TextureRegions as tiles side by side in a grid to get the ground plane. When the player clicks somewhere on the screen with the mouse, the main character is moving to that location, and the camera is following him. In other words: the main character always stays in the center of the screen / camera viewport while moving on the ground plane.

I am using a world space different from screen space, so I initialise the camera like this:

```
vWidth = game.screenWidth / 32;
vHeight = game.screenHeight / 32;
camera = new OrthographicCamera(vWidth, vHeight);
camera.position.set(vWidth / 2, vHeight / 2, 0f);
camera.update();
```

Now when the game starts with the camera on the initial position like shown above, everything is fine. The ground tiles are being rendered perfectly side by side, no gaps between them or anything. However, when the camera moves, then in some cases the tiles are not rendered perfectly any more, then I can see the background color shine through between all tiles as thin lines. In other words: In that case the tiles are rendered with gaps of 1-2 pixels in between them.

The drawing of the tiles is simple:

```
// final tileSize is the side length of one tile in world space, 2.0 in my case
spriteBatch.draw(tex, x, y, tileSize, tileSize);
```

However, this happens even if I move the camera only a tiny little bit from its original position. For debugging I print out the x coordinates in world space used when drawing the tiles. And in both cases, the original camera position as well as the camera position after the move, the x values used in the spriteBatch are exactly the same, eg.:

```
984.0 986.0 988.0 990.0 992.0 994.0 996.0 998.0
```

So I am wondering: If the drawing of tiles uses _exactly_ the same coordinates and size value in both cases, how can the problem with the background color shining through tiles only happen in some cases? Could it be related to the camera or viewport or anything like this?

PS: I just found out that I can work around this issue by using this draw command:

```
spriteBatch.draw(tex, x, y, tileSize * 1.01, tileSize * 1.01);
```

I can live with that, but it doesn't seem to be real solution...
